### Explore the YARN Cluster

msg.data: Explore the YARN Cluster

paragraphs.title: 1 - Visit the YARN Resource Manager
paragraphs.text:
%md
In a web browser on your remote desktop, visit the YARN Resource Manager (RM) UI by selecting `YARN` from the Services menu on the left side to open the YARN summary, and then selecting `Resource Manager UI` from the Quick Links section on the right.

No jobs are currently running so the current view shows the cluster "at rest."

msg.data:
In Firefox on your remote desktop, visit the YARN Resource Manager (RM) UI
using the provided bookmark (labeled YARN RM), or by going to URL http://localhost:8088/.
*** Does this link work? *** ***Remove “URL”?***

No jobs are currently running so the current view shows the cluster “at rest.”

Who Is Dr. Who?
You may notice that YARN says you are logged in as dr.who.
This is what the YARN UI displays when user authentication
is disabled for the cluster, as it is in the exercise environment.
If user authentication was enabled, you would have to log in
as a valid user to view the YARN UI, and your actual username
would be displayed, together with user metrics such as how many
applications you had run, how much of system resources your
applications used, and so on.

paragraphs.title: 2 - View the available metrics
paragraphs.text:
%md
Take note of the values in the **Cluster Overview** section, which displays information such as the number of applications running currently, previously run, or waiting to run; the amount of memory used and available; and how many worker nodes are in the cluster.

msg.data:
Take note of the values in the Cluster Metrics and Cluster Node Metrics sections,
which display information such as the number of applications running currently,

previously run, or waiting to run; the amount of memory used and available; and
how many worker nodes are in the cluster.

paragraphs.title: 3 - View the list of worker nodes
paragraphs.text:
%md
Click the **Nodes** link in the menu at the top of the page, it will display a list of worker nodes in the cluster.

paragraphs.title: 4 - Open the Node Manager UI
paragraphs.text:
%md
Click the link for one of the worker nodes under **Node HTTP Address** to open the Node Manager UI on that node (You may need to scroll to the right in the text box). This displays statistics about the selected node, including the amount of available memory, currently running applications, and so on.

Leave both the Resource Manager UI and the Node Manager UI open.

msg.data:
Click the localhost.localdomain:8042 link under Node HTTP Address to
open the Node Manager UI on that node. This displays statistics about the selected
node, including the amount of available memory, currently running applications
(there are none), and so on.

paragraphs.title: 5 - Update the Knowledge Base data files to HDFS

%sh
hdfs dfs -put /home/devuser/data/telco/kb /user/zeppelin/
hdfs dfs -ls /user/zeppelin/

paragraphs.title: 6 - Run an example program on the YARN cluster
paragraphs.text:
%md
Run the example `wordcount.py` program on the YARN cluster to count the frequency of words in the `kb` sample data file set.

The `spark-submit` command is used to submit a Spark program for execution on the cluster. Since Spark is managed by YARN on the course cluster, this gives us the opportunity to see how the YARN UI displays information about a running job. For now, focus on learning about the YARN UI.

While the application is running, view the YARN UI as described in the next steps. If it completes before you finish the exercise, simply rerun the application by executing the command for this step again.

msg.data:
Run the example wordcount.py program on the YARN cluster to count the
frequency of words in the sample data file set:

$ spark-submit $DEVSH/exercises/yarn/wordcount.py /devsh_loudacre/kb/*

The spark-submit command is used to submit a Spark program for execution on
the cluster. Since Spark is managed by YARN on the course cluster, this gives us the
opportunity to see how the YARN UI displays information about a running job. For
now, focus on learning about the YARN UI.

While the application is running, continue with the next steps. If it completes before
you finish the exercise, go to the terminal, press the up arrow until you get to the
spark-submit command again, and rerun the application.

paragraphs.text:
%sh
spark-submit /home/devuser/bin/devsh/exercises/yarn/wordcount.py /user/zeppelin/kb/*

paragraphs.title: 7 - Notice that the application is displayed in the YARN Resource Manager
paragraphs.text:
%md
Reload the YARN RM page in your web browser. Notice that the application you just started is displayed in the list of applications in the bottom section of the RM home page.

msg.data:
Reload the YARN RM page in Firefox. Notice that the application you just started is
displayed in the list of applications in the bottom section of the RM home page.

paragraphs.text:

View the YARN UI again to monitor the application

msg.data:

paragraphs.title: 8 - View the worker nodes
paragraphs.text:
%md
As you did in the first exercise sections, select **Nodes** from the menu at the top of the YARN RM page.

msg.data: As you did in the first exercise section, select Nodes.

paragraphs.title: 9 - Open the Node Manager UI
paragraphs.text:
%md
Reload the Node Manager UI.

msg.data: Select the node HTTP address link for localhost.localdomain to open the Node Manager UI.

paragraphs.title: 10 - View the applications running on the node
paragraphs.text:
%md
Now that an application is running, you can click **List of Applications on this Node** to see the application you submitted.

msg.data: Now that an application is running, you can click List of Applications to see the application you submitted.

paragraphs.title: 11 - View the containers allocated to the node
paragraphs.text:
